   "source": [
    "# Understanding Overlapping Distributions with Ridge Plots in R\n",
    "When visualizing data with continuous variables across different groups, one common challenge is dealing with overlapping distributions. Traditional plotting techniques such as histograms or density plots might not effectively convey the distributional differences between groups, especially when the data overlap significantly. This is where ridge plots come to the rescue! Ridge plots are a powerful visualization tool that allows us to represent and compare distributions across multiple groups, providing insights into the underlying data patterns.\n",
    "\n",
    "## What is a Ridge Plot?\n",
    "A ridge plot, also known as a joy plot, is a data visualization technique that displays the density of a continuous variable for different groups, stacked on top of each other. It is particularly useful when dealing with overlapping distributions, as it provides a clear and intuitive way to compare the shapes and spread of the distributions.\n",
    "\n",
    "The key feature of a ridge plot is the overlapping nature of the density ridges. Each ridge represents the density of the continuous variable within a specific group. The vertical position of the ridge indicates the group, while the width of the ridge represents the density of the data points. Where the ridges overlap, we can observe regions of high density, and where they separate, the density is lower.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Ridge Plots in R with ggridges\n",
    "To create ridge plots in R, we can use the **ggridges** package, which works in conjunction with the popular **ggplot2** library. Let's take a look at a simple example using the built-in **diamonds** dataset, which comes with R. We want to visualize the distribution of diamond prices for different cuts (quality of cut: Fair, Good, Very Good, Premium, and Ideal).\n",
    "\n"
   ]
